y; closed boundary relations should become a permeable innovation-community porch, entrance, or display window.\n- Make the update clearly about learning, making, prototyping, co-working, public demonstration, and community collaboration.\n\nFinal constraints:\n- Preserve the original camera viewpoint, perspective, major building geometry, street/yard layout, trees, and industrial waterfront identity.\n- Keep the result photorealistic and physically buildable as a real street or factory-edge scene, not a staged render or beautified park.\n- Keep the exact original image viewpoint and framing; do not rotate, zoom, crop differently, or change the camera height/lens feeling.\n- Do not add decorative lighting, warm ambient lighting, glowing light strips, or night-scene effects. If lighting is adjusted, only use realistic neutral white daylight/white functional light and minor brightness correction.\n- Use refined steel, glass, warm timber, robust paving, native planting, and believable human activity without weakening the real street-scene feeling.\n- Use icon-only wayfinding and abstract display graphics; no readable text, no logos, no fake words.\n- Avoid fantasy architecture, generic park beautification, excessive cars, empty-plaza feeling, and changes unrelated to innovation-community use."
